1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:00,180 --> 00:00:03,660
The flu epidemic has fully broken out in seven regions already.

3
00:00:03,780 --> 00:00:06,480
People are not following basic prevention rules.

4
00:00:07,080 --> 00:00:12,020
They linger in risk zones and don't maintain safe distance from the infected.

5
00:00:12,400 --> 00:00:18,180
The epidemic is also spreading because many still find a few hundred crowns for vaccination too much.

6
00:00:18,480 --> 00:00:19,720
Caution is free.

7
00:00:20,350 --> 00:00:24,330
Well well, what are you doing here in the risk zone?

8
00:00:24,550 --> 00:00:27,850
I came to make some immunity-boosting tea.

9
00:00:30,050 --> 00:00:32,750
That new haircut really suits you.

10
00:00:35,050 --> 00:00:36,350
You need something?

11
00:00:37,750 --> 00:00:39,050
Wanna play Crazy Eights?

12
00:00:39,410 --> 00:00:39,930
Please.

13
00:00:40,210 --> 00:00:42,150
I don't play with the infected, tell Ozzak.

14
00:00:42,950 --> 00:00:44,770
You're treating me like I have leprosy.

15
00:00:45,650 --> 00:00:51,650
Michal's got the premiere of his new musical on Thursday and I'm not missing it just because I catch the flu from my irresponsible daughter.

16
00:00:52,050 --> 00:00:53,590
I'm not irresponsible.

17
00:00:53,750 --> 00:00:55,050
I'm sick.

18
00:00:55,220 --> 00:00:56,820
You can't play with Ozzak.

19
00:00:56,820 --> 00:01:00,280
Every time he gets a ten, he gets a craving for beer.

20
00:01:00,550 --> 00:01:01,650
Do you know where my mug is?

21
00:01:01,820 --> 00:01:02,660
Can I have some tea?

22
00:01:06,250 --> 00:01:08,550
Iva, how could you?

23
00:01:09,150 --> 00:01:11,450
It's written right there.

24
00:01:12,650 --> 00:01:14,270
Fine, I'll wash it for you.

25
00:01:15,350 --> 00:01:16,250
No, wash it yourself.

26
00:01:23,650 --> 00:01:24,950
Do you know where we keep the bleach?

27
00:01:53,750 --> 00:01:54,850
I'm bringing medicine.

28
00:01:54,940 --> 00:01:55,420
I don't want it.

29
00:01:57,150 --> 00:01:59,480
Ivuska, don't be stubborn.

30
00:01:59,650 --> 00:02:02,350
Look, I'm just not going to treat myself with rum.

31
00:02:02,580 --> 00:02:05,760
You've been home for two weeks with your chemical crap.

32
00:02:05,940 --> 00:02:07,460
It's just eating you up from the inside.

33
00:02:07,480 --> 00:02:08,360
And rum doesn't, right?

34
00:02:09,050 --> 00:02:10,760
Rum is more like... warming.

35
00:02:11,750 --> 00:02:13,980
I don't need warming up when I have a fever.

36
00:02:15,350 --> 00:02:16,540
Ivuska, it's medicine.

37
00:02:16,540 --> 00:02:17,720
Does it say that anywhere?

38
00:02:17,820 --> 00:02:18,460
Yeah, where?

39
00:02:19,250 --> 00:02:19,950
Rapid Universal Medicine.

40
00:02:20,250 --> 00:02:24,550
I'd rather stick with my drops, okay?

41
00:02:25,080 --> 00:02:28,090
How about a game of Crazy Eights?

42
00:02:28,250 --> 00:02:28,610
Sure.

43
00:02:32,350 --> 00:02:33,250
Taking two?

44
00:02:33,550 --> 00:02:34,050
Hmm, damn.

45
00:02:43,250 --> 00:02:44,240
I need to take care of something.

46
00:02:44,240 --> 00:02:44,680
Sorry!

47
00:02:45,950 --> 00:02:46,750
Of course.

48
00:02:47,050 --> 00:02:48,450
Say hi to Simona.

49
00:02:57,900 --> 00:02:58,080
Hey.

50
00:02:58,440 --> 00:02:59,000
Oh right.

51
00:02:59,950 --> 00:03:00,950
When's Sasa coming?

52
00:03:00,980 --> 00:03:01,940
She's taking forever.

53
00:03:02,060 --> 00:03:02,540
Why?

54
00:03:02,920 --> 00:03:04,040
She's got a heavy bag.

55
00:03:04,920 --> 00:03:06,140
Come on in.

56
00:03:08,750 --> 00:03:09,950
Wanna play Crazy Eights?

57
00:03:09,950 --> 00:03:10,390
Me?

58
00:03:10,650 --> 00:03:11,210
Great.

59
00:03:19,590 --> 00:03:20,730
What's new at school?

60
00:03:21,110 --> 00:03:22,590
We're gonna have a test in Czech.

61
00:03:23,290 --> 00:03:23,850
What?

62
00:03:24,350 --> 00:03:24,910
What?

63
00:03:25,850 --> 00:03:27,750
Did you say we're gonna have a test in Czech?

64
00:03:27,790 --> 00:03:28,310
No.

65
00:03:28,850 --> 00:03:29,050
Yeah?

66
00:03:29,750 --> 00:03:32,150
I said we're going to have a written test in Czech.

67
00:03:36,050 --> 00:03:37,550
I brought you oranges.

68
00:03:37,950 --> 00:03:39,150
Oh, thanks.

69
00:03:40,050 --> 00:03:41,150
Want me to peel one for you?

70
00:03:41,890 --> 00:03:42,490
What?

71
00:03:43,650 --> 00:03:44,350
The orange.

72
00:03:44,450 --> 00:03:45,350
Peel it?

73
00:03:47,050 --> 00:03:47,950
Yeah, peel.

74
00:03:50,340 --> 00:03:50,840
Out.

75
00:03:51,970 --> 00:03:52,330
But...

76
00:03:52,330 --> 00:03:52,630
Out!

77
00:03:53,270 --> 00:03:53,870
Out!

78
00:03:59,250 --> 00:04:05,150
I never would have said Michal David would get into something so controversial.

79
00:04:05,650 --> 00:04:10,200
I read that he wanted to do Saint Wenceslas, but Janek Ledeck has already registered that.

80
00:04:10,750 --> 00:04:12,180
And why doesn't he do Masaryk?

81
00:04:12,650 --> 00:04:14,580
Osvaldova and Soukup already have that one.

82
00:04:14,950 --> 00:04:17,600
There's a huge fight over musical subjects, Tomas.

83
00:04:17,600 --> 00:04:18,880
There's an article about it right here.

84
00:04:19,550 --> 00:04:24,520
They write that among famous books only Dasenka is available, and among presidents only Zapotocky.

85
00:04:24,520 --> 00:04:26,440
Klaus is going to have a musical too?

86
00:04:26,860 --> 00:04:27,820
In the fall.

87
00:04:27,820 --> 00:04:29,550
Lucka Bila will play him.

88
00:04:31,550 --> 00:04:34,850
They also write here that Klaus will come to the premiere.

89
00:04:35,250 --> 00:04:38,590
Don't you really want to take Iva instead, if it's going to be such an event?

90
00:04:38,590 --> 00:04:39,550
She's still sick.

91
00:04:39,690 --> 00:04:40,550
Isn't she getting better?

92
00:04:40,730 --> 00:04:41,110
She is.

93
00:04:41,450 --> 00:04:43,350
She's stopped drinking from a sippy cup.

94
00:04:44,450 --> 00:04:46,450
You're overdoing it with the caution.

95
00:04:46,590 --> 00:04:50,150
I know very well how allergic Michal is to coughing in the audience.

96
00:04:50,190 --> 00:04:52,250
One throat clearing and he cancels the show.

97
00:04:52,370 --> 00:04:52,930
Really?

98
00:04:52,950 --> 00:04:53,270
Yes.

99
00:04:53,650 --> 00:04:57,630
Last year he had a concert in a lung clinic and didn't even finish the nonstop set.

100
00:04:58,150 --> 00:05:01,650
That would be quite embarrassing if the president didn't get to see the whole thing because of me.

101
00:05:02,350 --> 00:05:05,320
So I'll get to see a live president.

102
00:05:05,750 --> 00:05:07,440
And you've never seen one in person?

103
00:05:07,440 --> 00:05:07,760
Have you?

104
00:05:09,650 --> 00:05:14,450
In '88 I was at President Husak's meeting with the youth.

105
00:05:14,650 --> 00:05:17,480
It was called Socialism, the Future of Mankind.

106
00:05:17,480 --> 00:05:19,360
That must have been quite an event.

107
00:05:20,150 --> 00:05:22,350
I remember it perfectly.

108
00:05:22,650 --> 00:05:28,350
We all had to bring indoor shoes because they'd just laid new linoleum in the Spanish Hall.

109
00:05:28,850 --> 00:05:31,560
Segman forgot his, so he had to stand there in his socks.

110
00:05:32,050 --> 00:05:39,750
Then they played the Song of Labor, the president came in, shook all our hands, said "how are you" and we went home.

111
00:05:40,950 --> 00:05:44,720
Segman had to take a taxi because someone hid his shoes.

112
00:05:46,050 --> 00:05:47,010
And what about the president?

113
00:05:47,150 --> 00:05:48,050
What was he like?

114
00:05:49,450 --> 00:05:54,150
Well, I remember he faintly smelled of cabbage.

115
00:06:00,900 --> 00:06:01,700
Here's two more.

116
00:06:05,730 --> 00:06:06,370
What is it?

117
00:06:06,850 --> 00:06:09,750
There's a bear tied up and someone's beating it.

118
00:06:10,750 --> 00:06:11,440
Jesus.

119
00:06:11,440 --> 00:06:12,920
I'll pick a different game.

120
00:06:13,140 --> 00:06:14,520
Yeah, but put the bear on the bottom.

121
00:06:17,750 --> 00:06:19,250
That dog is dead.

122
00:06:19,750 --> 00:06:20,850
It's just sleeping.

123
00:06:22,250 --> 00:06:23,050
You think?

124
00:06:27,450 --> 00:06:28,850
I'm done with this.

125
00:06:28,950 --> 00:06:30,950
I've been stuck at home all week.

126
00:06:30,950 --> 00:06:36,250
Ozzak treats me with rum, Lexa keeps staring at me, Dad's disgusted by me, and you're afraid of a stomach ace.

127
00:06:37,250 --> 00:06:40,650
She looks like Mom when Lexa shaves with her razor.

128
00:06:41,100 --> 00:06:42,700
Let me try another one.

129
00:06:42,900 --> 00:06:43,520
Forget it.

130
00:06:44,450 --> 00:06:47,750
There's a dog, a mouse, the mouse is riding the dog, that's funny.

131
00:06:47,860 --> 00:06:49,380
Wouldn't you rather play Scrabble?

132
00:06:49,380 --> 00:06:51,800
How about I tell you what happened at school instead?

133
00:06:51,800 --> 00:06:52,420
Sure, great.

134
00:06:52,560 --> 00:06:53,480
What's everyone up to?

135
00:06:53,540 --> 00:06:53,960
What about Benes?

136
00:06:54,140 --> 00:06:55,920
I don't know, but we're having a Czech test.

137
00:06:57,200 --> 00:06:59,060
Lexa said, well, he tried to say.

138
00:06:59,060 --> 00:07:03,390
It's after Wolker, so copy it, because Tokarska said she won't excuse late absences.

139
00:07:03,390 --> 00:07:04,210
She can go to hell.

140
00:07:06,250 --> 00:07:07,650
Why is it all smudged?

141
00:07:08,550 --> 00:07:11,850
Because that Wolker had such a sad fate.

142
00:07:12,350 --> 00:07:14,850
So you were crying again, like when we did Nemcova?

143
00:07:15,450 --> 00:07:17,150
It was such a tough class.

144
00:07:17,950 --> 00:07:19,580
Great, now I can't even read it.

145
00:07:19,750 --> 00:07:21,550
Then copy it from Lexa.

146
00:07:22,450 --> 00:07:24,290
You carry Lexa's stuff in your bag?

147
00:07:24,550 --> 00:07:26,530
Well, his bag got taken by an orangutan at the zoo.

148
00:07:26,530 --> 00:07:26,730
Oh right?

149
00:07:27,150 --> 00:07:30,070
So Mom said it's not worth buying another one for the few years left.

150
00:07:31,150 --> 00:07:32,910
Shouldn't Lexa be carrying the bag instead?

151
00:07:33,450 --> 00:07:34,550
We take turns.

152
00:07:35,150 --> 00:07:36,450
This year it's my turn.

153
00:07:39,650 --> 00:07:41,950
Geez, he even copied the poems.

154
00:07:42,250 --> 00:07:43,320
Holy Hills.

155
00:07:43,320 --> 00:07:44,660
More like Holy Hill, right?

156
00:07:44,720 --> 00:07:45,700
He probably miswrote it.

157
00:07:46,550 --> 00:07:50,820
The boobs of Iva Pacovska, they're really enormous?

158
00:07:55,650 --> 00:07:56,450
I've had enough!

159
00:07:56,610 --> 00:08:00,010
When we run the fifteen hundred, Lexa runs backwards to see my boobs.

160
00:08:00,090 --> 00:08:05,310
In family education he grabbed my butt, and I threw out the baby with the bathwater, and now he's going to write dirty poems about me?

161
00:08:05,450 --> 00:08:07,950
And to top it off, he thinks they're really enormous.

162
00:08:09,150 --> 00:08:12,050
Young Krutova's boobs, those aren't like that anymore.

163
00:08:12,350 --> 00:08:14,050
Is he blind or what?

164
00:08:14,850 --> 00:08:19,760
Krutova is excused from gym class because she knocked her teeth out on the trampoline with those things.

165
00:08:20,050 --> 00:08:21,750
I don't have D cups.

166
00:08:22,050 --> 00:08:23,480
I think it's metonymy.

167
00:08:23,480 --> 00:08:24,400
Copy that too.

168
00:08:25,550 --> 00:08:26,240
What's that?

169
00:08:26,250 --> 00:08:29,350
A figurative expression based on inner similarity.

170
00:08:30,050 --> 00:08:31,350
Now it's all much clearer.

171
00:08:33,050 --> 00:08:37,650
Lexa says your boobs are perfect and just the right size.

172
00:08:39,150 --> 00:08:39,950
For the hand.

173
00:08:40,750 --> 00:08:41,850
Wait, wait, wait.

174
00:08:42,150 --> 00:08:45,230
He talks to you about my boobs?

175
00:08:45,230 --> 00:08:45,490
Yeah.

176
00:08:45,950 --> 00:08:49,870
Mom refuses to discuss it with him and he's too embarrassed in front of Mr. Ozzak.

177
00:08:50,050 --> 00:08:51,550
And that doesn't bother you?

178
00:08:52,350 --> 00:08:53,950
You get used to it.

179
00:08:54,660 --> 00:08:55,180
Yeah.

180
00:08:56,450 --> 00:08:58,050
When he can't sleep, he counts them.

181
00:08:58,460 --> 00:08:59,680
That bugs me a little.

182
00:09:05,350 --> 00:09:06,950
I've tried everything.

183
00:09:06,990 --> 00:09:08,190
I dropped it on sugar for her.

184
00:09:08,210 --> 00:09:09,370
I put it in her tea.

185
00:09:09,410 --> 00:09:10,850
I even made rum mashed potatoes.

186
00:09:11,210 --> 00:09:12,850
But she just refuses to take the medicine.

187
00:09:12,990 --> 00:09:14,130
That's because you're spoiling her.

188
00:09:14,630 --> 00:09:15,150
How so?

189
00:09:15,370 --> 00:09:16,630
Well, anyone would love that.

190
00:09:16,690 --> 00:09:18,290
Lying around at home in the warm, watching TV.

191
00:09:19,050 --> 00:09:24,450
I just turn off the heating, the electricity, throw a bat into the room, and the next day she's happy to go cough her way to school.

192
00:09:26,050 --> 00:09:26,760
Hey, Lexa.

193
00:09:27,050 --> 00:09:28,100
Hi there, Bejku.

194
00:09:28,100 --> 00:09:28,820
One lemonade.

195
00:09:29,520 --> 00:09:30,960
Did the tap water run out?

196
00:09:31,080 --> 00:09:32,380
I'll pay for it.

197
00:09:35,250 --> 00:09:35,950
What's wrong?

198
00:09:37,250 --> 00:09:39,550
I brought her oranges and she kicked me out.

199
00:09:40,150 --> 00:09:42,020
She won't take medicine, I told you.

200
00:09:42,020 --> 00:09:44,440
The flu has to be treated, otherwise it can develop into something worse.

201
00:09:44,480 --> 00:09:45,260
What a mess.

202
00:09:45,340 --> 00:09:48,360
Nonsense, my mom always said the flu needs to be walked off.

203
00:09:48,480 --> 00:09:52,960
Yeah, I once tried to walk off the flu at the pub and I ended up with twelve bumps on my forehead.

204
00:09:53,480 --> 00:09:54,940
When you sneeze, you gotta hold onto your beer.

205
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:57,400
That can't even stand up.

206
00:09:57,760 --> 00:09:58,600
What if it can?

207
00:09:59,280 --> 00:10:00,900
She's coughing a little, you're making a big deal of it.

208
00:10:00,900 --> 00:10:03,950
And by the way, that guy we studied today who died of a cough, did he die?

209
00:10:04,020 --> 00:10:04,940
He probably didn't want to get treated.

210
00:10:05,200 --> 00:10:06,500
Must have been some weakling.

211
00:10:06,540 --> 00:10:08,280
And by the way, Tokarska said he was a great man.

212
00:10:08,850 --> 00:10:12,700
He was the one who wrote that poem about getting smaller and smaller.

213
00:10:12,700 --> 00:10:13,060
A poem?

214
00:10:13,550 --> 00:10:14,650
Lexa, you know what we agreed on?

215
00:10:14,850 --> 00:10:18,050
What's wrong with poems?

216
00:10:18,250 --> 00:10:20,050
Every man should write one once in a while.

217
00:10:20,350 --> 00:10:22,850
Mr. Ozzak, you write poems too.

218
00:10:23,550 --> 00:10:26,850
Usually it hits me about an hour after lunch.

219
00:10:28,350 --> 00:10:29,710
Maybe we could learn that in your shop too.

220
00:10:29,890 --> 00:10:31,450
Nonsense, nobody reads books, Lexa.

221
00:10:31,750 --> 00:10:34,690
If you want people to read it, you have to shove it right in their face.

222
00:10:35,010 --> 00:10:37,410
Lexa is not going to write any poems.

223
00:10:37,590 --> 00:10:38,650
We're speaking hypothetically.

224
00:10:39,750 --> 00:10:40,570
So where then?

225
00:10:40,890 --> 00:10:41,350
Where.

226
00:10:42,450 --> 00:10:45,250
Where people have to go and where they have time to read.

227
00:10:45,950 --> 00:10:49,840
Ozzak, so you're the one writing those dirty poems on the bathroom door.

228
00:10:49,840 --> 00:10:51,160
On the bathroom door?

229
00:10:51,970 --> 00:10:52,430
Awesome!

230
00:10:52,870 --> 00:10:53,450
Hold on, hold on.

231
00:10:54,550 --> 00:10:55,650
And who's going to pay?

232
00:10:56,650 --> 00:10:57,350
Mr. Ozzak...

233
00:10:57,450 --> 00:10:58,850
You got twelve crowns?

234
00:11:00,850 --> 00:11:04,550
Sure, Lexa, go ahead, I'll cover for you.

235
00:11:06,550 --> 00:11:07,550
Put it on my brother's tab.

236
00:11:14,650 --> 00:11:15,950
Don't you feel weird?

237
00:11:18,340 --> 00:11:20,560
I'm simply following basic prevention rules.

238
00:11:20,740 --> 00:11:22,880
But if you don't like it, I can leave.

239
00:11:26,450 --> 00:11:28,210
That cough of yours isn't getting any better.

240
00:11:28,210 --> 00:11:28,730
Better?

241
00:11:29,250 --> 00:11:31,350
Ozzak was complaining that you won't take medicine.

242
00:11:31,490 --> 00:11:32,990
Ozzak's the one who needs treatment.

243
00:11:36,040 --> 00:11:36,720
Hi, Iva.

244
00:11:38,080 --> 00:11:39,840
What's up, Lexa, you scared of me?

245
00:11:41,880 --> 00:11:42,860
It's prevention.

246
00:11:43,320 --> 00:11:44,600
Don't you wanna play Crazy Eights with Iva?

247
00:11:44,780 --> 00:11:45,020
No.

248
00:11:47,550 --> 00:11:48,050
Iva, Sasa said you have my Czech notebook.

249
00:11:51,080 --> 00:11:53,260
Sasa told me what you count when you can't fall asleep.

250
00:11:55,010 --> 00:11:55,650
Can I have it?

251
00:11:56,030 --> 00:11:56,390
No.

252
00:11:57,150 --> 00:11:59,250
Wait, Iva, you haven't copied it yet?

253
00:11:59,350 --> 00:12:00,050
I haven't.

254
00:12:00,100 --> 00:12:02,600
And I'd rather nobody else copied it either.

255
00:12:02,820 --> 00:12:04,420
Come on Iva, that's selfish.

256
00:12:04,600 --> 00:12:05,460
That's prevention.

257
00:12:06,450 --> 00:12:07,650
It was just the beginning.

258
00:12:07,950 --> 00:12:11,260
I'd recommend you don't take it any further.

259
00:12:11,260 --> 00:12:12,420
I meant well.

260
00:12:13,250 --> 00:12:15,950
Wait, are you still talking about the notebook?

261
00:12:16,250 --> 00:12:17,150
Of course.

262
00:12:17,650 --> 00:12:20,710
Right, I'll just take the notebook and go.

263
00:12:21,150 --> 00:12:22,610
The notebook stays here.

264
00:12:22,850 --> 00:12:27,390
And if I were you, I wouldn't stick my snout in here again, or you'll get smacked across it.

265
00:12:27,390 --> 00:12:30,390
Come on Iva, Lexa doesn't have a snout.

266
00:12:30,610 --> 00:12:31,450
That was metonymy.

267
00:12:34,110 --> 00:12:34,810
Well well.

268
00:12:40,550 --> 00:12:43,750
Tomas, the first review is out.

269
00:12:43,760 --> 00:12:44,260
Already?

270
00:12:44,780 --> 00:12:45,280
Listen.

271
00:12:46,670 --> 00:12:53,110
The gripping duet of Hitler and Mussolini, Decibels of War, draws from the very best we've known from Michal David.

272
00:12:53,490 --> 00:12:55,910
But what the audience can really look forward to.

273
00:12:55,930 --> 00:12:58,290
Is the vocal choir of the Laughing Beasts.

274
00:12:59,130 --> 00:13:00,690
Well, that's gonna be a hit.

275
00:13:01,150 --> 00:13:04,130
I heard the opening song this morning, it really got to me.

276
00:13:04,190 --> 00:13:05,010
Wait, how did it go?

277
00:13:05,750 --> 00:13:10,750
They'll be executed, they'll be executed, na, na, na, na, na.

278
00:13:10,830 --> 00:13:11,630
Something like that.

279
00:13:11,630 --> 00:13:14,650
That'll be K.H. Frank's aria from the second act.

280
00:13:15,650 --> 00:13:17,690
And did you know Michal David actually plays a role himself?

281
00:13:17,690 --> 00:13:18,070
Really?

282
00:13:18,070 --> 00:13:18,290
Yeah.

283
00:13:19,750 --> 00:13:34,120
The author himself, with charming modesty, takes only the small role of Saint Wenceslas, who in the stunning finale saves the nation by riding out of the mountain on a white horse with the Blanik knights, played by the historical fencing group Palecek.

284
00:13:34,120 --> 00:13:35,040
Who wrote this?

285
00:13:35,040 --> 00:13:39,060
Vladimir Stancel, he specializes in Michal David.

286
00:13:39,550 --> 00:13:42,560
I also need to buy a poster and ask him to sign it for Iva.

287
00:13:42,560 --> 00:13:42,680
Yeah.

288
00:13:43,150 --> 00:13:46,560
Even though she doesn't deserve it at all, she's absolutely unbearable.

289
00:13:46,560 --> 00:13:47,580
She's probably not feeling well.

290
00:13:47,580 --> 00:13:50,680
I tell you, I'll be glad to get out of the house for a bit.

291
00:14:02,850 --> 00:14:03,950
Only six?

292
00:14:04,250 --> 00:14:05,550
She got medicine.

293
00:14:05,950 --> 00:14:06,850
Antibiotics?

294
00:14:07,430 --> 00:14:08,710
More like a syrup.

295
00:14:11,050 --> 00:14:12,150
In a banana.

296
00:14:13,860 --> 00:14:14,780
Thank God.

297
00:14:14,940 --> 00:14:16,280
Hopefully she'll be even better tomorrow.

298
00:14:16,460 --> 00:14:16,940
Definitely.

299
00:14:17,650 --> 00:14:19,220
And if not, she's got a bucket by the bed.

300
00:14:21,550 --> 00:14:22,440
Cheers, bro.

301
00:14:22,850 --> 00:14:24,150
What would I do without you.

302
00:14:25,710 --> 00:14:26,430
What's this?

303
00:14:27,050 --> 00:14:27,550
I don't know.

304
00:14:28,950 --> 00:14:31,350
Lexa Ales Krabe.

305
00:14:33,150 --> 00:14:38,150
The boobs of Iva Pacovska, they're really enormous.

306
00:14:39,550 --> 00:14:42,350
Wow bro, you're a poet.

307
00:14:47,850 --> 00:14:49,100
One Wolker, please.

308
00:14:49,100 --> 00:14:49,660
What's up?

309
00:14:50,550 --> 00:14:51,540
Well, you're kind of one too.

310
00:14:52,150 --> 00:14:53,350
You've got a poet at home.

311
00:14:55,550 --> 00:14:56,850
And look in the back, by the Wolker.

312
00:14:57,850 --> 00:14:59,660
That's why I ordered the Wolker.

313
00:14:59,660 --> 00:15:00,740
Well, as a joke.

314
00:15:02,550 --> 00:15:03,930
I'll have a beer.

315
00:15:04,250 --> 00:15:08,350
Iva is beautiful like a statue, because she isn't flat.

316
00:15:08,750 --> 00:15:11,250
I clearly told him poems should be banned.

317
00:15:11,550 --> 00:15:13,100
Come on, kid, that's so silly.

318
00:15:13,100 --> 00:15:13,680
Silly, huh?

319
00:15:14,450 --> 00:15:16,450
He once sent this to a children's magazine.

320
00:15:18,750 --> 00:15:20,250
Mommy, mommy, mommy, why are we always alone?

321
00:15:20,350 --> 00:15:26,150
We're cold, we're hungry, come take care of us.

322
00:15:26,850 --> 00:15:28,250
And he was nine years old.

323
00:15:31,050 --> 00:15:32,730
Well, he's got a nice rhyme going.

324
00:15:33,150 --> 00:15:36,390
Yeah, but try explaining poetic license to social services.

325
00:15:36,750 --> 00:15:37,850
He takes after his dad.

326
00:15:38,500 --> 00:15:40,340
He's the one who got me into poems.

327
00:15:40,600 --> 00:15:41,940
Well those must be better than this, right?

328
00:15:43,550 --> 00:15:46,050
The boobs of my Simona are like two little lemons.

329
00:15:46,110 --> 00:15:48,410
Wait, you're not gonna pick up any girl with something that stupid.

330
00:15:48,510 --> 00:15:50,630
You have no idea how that turns a girl on.

331
00:15:51,450 --> 00:15:54,510
First he tried the sweet stuff on me, like my love, you smell like rain.

332
00:15:54,510 --> 00:15:55,570
Wait, rain, right?

333
00:15:55,790 --> 00:15:56,270
Tar.

334
00:15:56,750 --> 00:15:59,350
You know I used to work as an asphalt layer.

335
00:16:00,150 --> 00:16:02,950
So I threw that one back in his face, and he tried again.

336
00:16:03,050 --> 00:16:07,440
But as soon as he pinned the lemons poem on my door, I went crazy for him.

337
00:16:07,750 --> 00:16:09,750
And we spent a week sweating in a trailer.

338
00:16:27,270 --> 00:16:28,910
You can't ring six times.

339
00:16:29,570 --> 00:16:30,050
Sorry.

340
00:16:30,770 --> 00:16:31,650
How are you feeling?

341
00:16:31,990 --> 00:16:32,470
Lousy.

342
00:16:33,350 --> 00:16:34,550
But I've stopped coughing.

343
00:16:36,770 --> 00:16:38,190
What day is it?

344
00:16:38,510 --> 00:16:39,030
Thursday.

345
00:16:39,350 --> 00:16:40,450
That can't be.

346
00:16:41,350 --> 00:16:44,050
The last thing I remember is eating a banana on Tuesday.

347
00:16:44,850 --> 00:16:48,760
I rang yesterday and Mr. Ozzak said you were at a checkup, you don't remember?

348
00:16:49,150 --> 00:16:51,250
Nothing since the banana.

349
00:16:52,650 --> 00:16:53,950
Anything new at school?

350
00:16:54,110 --> 00:16:54,930
Lots of stuff.

351
00:16:54,930 --> 00:17:00,880
In Czech the Slovak cultural foundation, in shop class screws and bolts, and in math matrices.

352
00:17:00,880 --> 00:17:02,920
I never understand what you're talking about.

353
00:17:03,160 --> 00:17:03,980
I'll let you copy it.

354
00:17:05,750 --> 00:17:07,240
So nothing interesting.

355
00:17:07,240 --> 00:17:07,380
No.

356
00:17:08,250 --> 00:17:10,880
Except for the rush at the boys' bathroom during break.

357
00:17:10,880 --> 00:17:12,100
Was it the spitting contest again?

358
00:17:12,750 --> 00:17:14,850
I don't know, but Lexa got detention for it.

359
00:17:15,550 --> 00:17:17,550
So, the spitting contest.

360
00:17:17,830 --> 00:17:18,490
Anything else?

361
00:17:18,950 --> 00:17:20,450
Some seniors were asking about you.

362
00:17:20,650 --> 00:17:21,150
About me?

363
00:17:21,150 --> 00:17:21,850
What did they want?

364
00:17:21,850 --> 00:17:27,050
Well, when they found out you weren't there, they wanted your phone number.

365
00:17:28,250 --> 00:17:32,890
At first I didn't want to give it to them, but they took my biology notebook and started ripping out pages.

366
00:17:32,890 --> 00:17:34,590
35 new texts?

367
00:17:35,550 --> 00:17:36,650
From guys?

368
00:17:37,450 --> 00:17:38,450
Hey, who's Tibor?

369
00:17:38,650 --> 00:17:40,750
Oh, that troublemaker from the senior class.

370
00:17:40,750 --> 00:17:41,730
The one with the motorcycle?

371
00:17:42,250 --> 00:17:46,050
I don't know, but he was the worst of them, he ripped out my arthropods chapter.

372
00:17:47,250 --> 00:17:48,350
Oh my God, oh my God!

373
00:17:48,850 --> 00:17:49,950
Benes is texting me.

374
00:17:50,350 --> 00:17:54,150
Hi Iva, we all miss you here, some more than others.

375
00:17:54,600 --> 00:17:55,980
Aren't you lonely at home?

376
00:17:56,000 --> 00:17:56,700
How's the flu?

377
00:17:57,060 --> 00:17:58,480
Do you need any vitamins?

378
00:17:59,150 --> 00:18:01,260
I'm free tonight, I could come over.

379
00:18:01,260 --> 00:18:01,820
Benes.

380
00:18:03,050 --> 00:18:06,050
Sasa, Benes wants to come to my place tonight.

381
00:18:06,550 --> 00:18:07,650
The answer is?

382
00:18:08,250 --> 00:18:08,810
Yes.

383
00:18:08,990 --> 00:18:09,290
Iva!

384
00:18:10,030 --> 00:18:10,410
What?

385
00:18:11,050 --> 00:18:13,250
Dad's going to the premiere and Ozzak will be at the pub.

386
00:18:13,550 --> 00:18:15,010
Benes is going out with Machova.

387
00:18:15,450 --> 00:18:17,710
So what, does Machova have a patent on him?

388
00:18:17,950 --> 00:18:19,250
She does kickboxing.

389
00:18:19,650 --> 00:18:23,710
Kropackova just lingered with Benes in the locker room and ended up eating through a straw for six weeks.

390
00:18:23,710 --> 00:18:24,710
You're sick, quit being silly.

391
00:18:25,350 --> 00:18:26,450
It's no big deal.

392
00:18:26,850 --> 00:18:29,190
He'll bring me tangerines, we'll just kiss.

393
00:18:29,190 --> 00:18:29,710
Iva.

394
00:18:31,050 --> 00:18:33,350
Talk, I meant to say talk.

395
00:18:34,450 --> 00:18:37,400
Oh, you're up?

396
00:18:37,400 --> 00:18:37,600
Yeah.

397
00:18:38,150 --> 00:18:40,150
And how are you feeling?

398
00:18:40,160 --> 00:18:40,720
Fine.

399
00:18:43,050 --> 00:18:50,750
Fine, fine, fine, fine, fine, fine, fine, fine.

400
00:18:51,450 --> 00:18:53,550
That's great, fine.

401
00:18:54,070 --> 00:18:54,630
Dad?

402
00:18:54,830 --> 00:18:54,990
Yeah?

403
00:18:55,750 --> 00:18:56,650
Are you okay?

404
00:18:57,950 --> 00:18:58,440
Why?

405
00:18:58,550 --> 00:19:01,450
Well, you just said "fine" about seventeen times.

406
00:19:01,740 --> 00:19:02,300
Really?

407
00:19:02,850 --> 00:19:03,450
Yeah.

408
00:19:06,450 --> 00:19:07,550
Well, I'm off.

409
00:19:07,750 --> 00:19:08,950
It's not Lexa, is it?

410
00:19:09,120 --> 00:19:09,680
No.

411
00:19:10,750 --> 00:19:11,550
Good.

412
00:19:16,430 --> 00:19:17,090
Do you get it?

413
00:19:17,700 --> 00:19:18,260
No.

414
00:19:26,160 --> 00:19:26,700
Hello.

415
00:19:26,820 --> 00:19:27,700
Hi, Lexa.

416
00:19:28,470 --> 00:19:29,350
Is Mr. Ozzak here?

417
00:19:29,570 --> 00:19:29,730
No.

418
00:19:30,230 --> 00:19:30,750
Oh.

419
00:19:31,650 --> 00:19:32,270
Will he be back?

420
00:19:32,450 --> 00:19:36,450
He went to see Mr. Metlos, so I figure he'll show up by the end of the week.

421
00:19:38,750 --> 00:19:40,250
I wanted to ask something.

422
00:19:40,650 --> 00:19:45,640
If you were a woman and somebody upset you, what would he have to do for you to forgive him?

423
00:19:46,150 --> 00:19:47,680
An apology always helps.

424
00:19:47,950 --> 00:19:50,250
And if you add a flower on top of that?

425
00:19:50,550 --> 00:19:52,180
Mom says flowers are for sissies.

426
00:19:52,550 --> 00:19:54,850
That women appreciate a cash gift more.

427
00:19:55,950 --> 00:19:57,050
Every woman is different.

428
00:19:57,350 --> 00:19:59,950
But a flower always works on a normal woman.

429
00:20:01,140 --> 00:20:02,420
Could I borrow this one?

430
00:20:02,420 --> 00:20:04,650
No, that one's for Michal David.

431
00:20:05,130 --> 00:20:05,590
Oh.

432
00:20:06,270 --> 00:20:06,990
And this one?

433
00:20:07,850 --> 00:20:09,450
That's for his horse.

434
00:20:10,350 --> 00:20:12,940
We're going to the premiere tonight and I'm bringing them on stage.

435
00:20:12,940 --> 00:20:13,860
Is Mr. Pacovsky going too?

436
00:20:14,100 --> 00:20:14,560
Of course.

437
00:20:14,580 --> 00:20:15,940
He was even invited.

438
00:20:15,940 --> 00:20:17,650
I'm just his escort.

439
00:20:18,650 --> 00:20:19,950
Then I'll sort it out today.

440
00:20:21,250 --> 00:20:22,150
Wish me luck.

441
00:20:22,390 --> 00:20:22,850
Goodbye.

442
00:20:23,750 --> 00:20:24,370
Good day.

443
00:20:24,670 --> 00:20:29,340
What did he want?

444
00:20:29,340 --> 00:20:33,050
Oh, he's having some trouble in love.

445
00:20:33,150 --> 00:20:36,630
But I'm sure he and his sweetheart will sort it out tonight.

446
00:20:36,630 --> 00:20:37,110
Oh dear.

447
00:20:38,850 --> 00:20:45,460
Tomas, I was thinking you could go up on stage first and give this to the horse.

448
00:20:45,460 --> 00:20:48,900
Because the florist said asparagus calms horses down.

449
00:20:49,120 --> 00:20:50,080
What else did he say?

450
00:20:50,240 --> 00:20:52,340
That when a horse sees asparagus, it goes for it.

451
00:20:52,880 --> 00:20:54,200
No, what did Lexa say?

452
00:20:54,460 --> 00:20:55,100
Actually, nothing.

453
00:20:55,600 --> 00:20:58,680
It would be very kind of you to take care of the horse.

454
00:20:58,760 --> 00:21:01,120
You see, I'm terribly afraid of those creatures.

455
00:21:01,380 --> 00:21:01,860
Marcelka.

456
00:21:02,350 --> 00:21:05,410
I'm afraid I won't be presenting any bouquet tonight.

457
00:21:08,080 --> 00:21:08,600
Excuse me?

458
00:21:08,600 --> 00:21:09,850
I'm just not going anywhere.

459
00:21:10,150 --> 00:21:12,720
You said you wouldn't be presenting any...

460
00:21:12,720 --> 00:21:14,160
You're not going?

461
00:21:14,500 --> 00:21:15,200
Family reasons.

462
00:21:15,380 --> 00:21:16,140
Did something happen?

463
00:21:16,200 --> 00:21:16,460
It could.

464
00:21:16,680 --> 00:21:17,800
But you were so looking forward to it.

465
00:21:17,800 --> 00:21:19,660
Well, sometimes sacrifices must be made.

466
00:21:19,750 --> 00:21:22,200
That's the name of Eduard Benes's aria from the prologue.

467
00:21:22,200 --> 00:21:23,520
You can tell me about it tomorrow.

468
00:21:32,850 --> 00:21:34,050
Well, I'm off.

469
00:21:34,850 --> 00:21:36,110
Have a great time.

470
00:21:36,350 --> 00:21:37,250
Yeah, I will.

471
00:21:38,550 --> 00:21:39,350
When will you be back?

472
00:21:39,440 --> 00:21:39,960
Why?

473
00:21:40,740 --> 00:21:41,260
Well.

474
00:21:41,260 --> 00:21:43,720
So I know when to expect you.

475
00:21:43,850 --> 00:21:46,020
Well, don't wait up for me tonight, no, I...

476
00:21:47,050 --> 00:21:48,480
You know, premiere, reception.

477
00:21:48,850 --> 00:21:50,760
I haven't seen Michal in years.

478
00:21:50,950 --> 00:21:52,160
Right, say hi to him then.

479
00:21:52,160 --> 00:21:52,380
Yeah, yeah.

480
00:21:53,950 --> 00:21:55,150
You've got everything?

481
00:21:55,270 --> 00:21:55,790
Why?

482
00:21:57,050 --> 00:21:59,650
Well, so you don't have to come back.

483
00:22:00,250 --> 00:22:02,190
Oh, I wouldn't come back, no, I...

484
00:22:02,850 --> 00:22:05,250
Once I head out, I don't come back.

485
00:22:08,750 --> 00:22:11,340
Have a good time, you two.

486
00:22:11,550 --> 00:22:13,750
You sure you don't want to come with me after all?

487
00:22:13,950 --> 00:22:15,240
Marcelka will understand.

488
00:22:15,240 --> 00:22:15,700
No.

489
00:22:16,250 --> 00:22:17,620
I just don't feel up to it yet.

490
00:22:17,620 --> 00:22:18,120
Too bad.

491
00:22:19,550 --> 00:22:20,350
Well, bye.

492
00:22:20,450 --> 00:22:21,800
And get better.

493
00:22:21,800 --> 00:22:22,580
I will, I will.

494
00:22:22,660 --> 00:22:23,080
Bye bye.

495
00:22:23,740 --> 00:22:24,140
Bye.

496
00:22:58,350 --> 00:23:00,450
Renata, what are you doing here?

497
00:23:00,950 --> 00:23:02,650
I came to chat.

498
00:23:02,950 --> 00:23:04,470
What do you want to chat about?

499
00:23:04,710 --> 00:23:05,450
About Benes.

500
00:23:05,810 --> 00:23:06,590
What happened to him?

501
00:23:07,050 --> 00:23:08,950
Nothing serious, just bruises.

502
00:23:09,150 --> 00:23:13,090
He'll be fine soon, though texting will be tough for a few days.

503
00:23:13,090 --> 00:23:14,610
He just wanted to bring me tangerines.

504
00:23:15,050 --> 00:23:18,450
You'd think after what happened to Kropackova, everyone would be careful.

505
00:23:18,850 --> 00:23:19,550
But no.

506
00:23:20,050 --> 00:23:23,270
Every girl without a boyfriend will keep trying it with him.

507
00:23:23,270 --> 00:23:23,950
But that's not me.

508
00:23:24,940 --> 00:23:26,000
I have a boyfriend.

509
00:23:26,040 --> 00:23:26,680
Sure.

510
00:23:26,780 --> 00:23:28,200
No, wait, wait, wait, wait, wait.

511
00:23:28,260 --> 00:23:29,440
I really am going out with someone.

512
00:23:29,520 --> 00:23:29,820
Really.

513
00:23:29,860 --> 00:23:30,780
Nobody knows about it.

514
00:23:32,150 --> 00:23:33,150
We're keeping it secret.

515
00:23:33,770 --> 00:23:34,850
Because of my dad.

516
00:23:34,850 --> 00:23:38,510
He's a total psycho and if he found out, he'd kill us both.

517
00:23:38,510 --> 00:23:39,490
So who are you going out with?

518
00:23:40,400 --> 00:23:42,040
That's exactly what I can't tell you.

519
00:23:42,080 --> 00:23:43,380
What if your dad got it out of you?

520
00:23:43,750 --> 00:23:46,550
Can your father do a roundhouse kick with his heel?

521
00:23:46,950 --> 00:23:47,740
Probably not.

522
00:23:48,050 --> 00:23:49,050
Then relax.

523
00:23:50,350 --> 00:23:53,550
Geez, Mr. Ozzak forgot his keys again, right?

524
00:23:53,580 --> 00:23:54,060
Iva!

525
00:23:54,750 --> 00:23:56,750
Good thing you're here, come on.

526
00:23:57,870 --> 00:23:58,810
So that's him.

527
00:24:00,150 --> 00:24:01,950
Whoa, Machova, what are you doing here?

528
00:24:02,050 --> 00:24:03,250
Bucek, right.

529
00:24:03,250 --> 00:24:03,650
Yeah.

530
00:24:04,580 --> 00:24:05,060
What?

531
00:24:05,060 --> 00:24:06,900
He just wouldn't have occurred to me.

532
00:24:06,900 --> 00:24:08,300
Yeah, me neither at first.

533
00:24:08,600 --> 00:24:09,760
But he's great.

534
00:24:10,150 --> 00:24:14,020
Sensitive, attentive, hard-working.

535
00:24:14,450 --> 00:24:16,250
Where are you taking that ficus, Lexa?

536
00:24:16,880 --> 00:24:17,840
It's for you.

537
00:24:19,650 --> 00:24:20,450
See?

538
00:24:20,550 --> 00:24:21,770
He's always bringing me flowers.

539
00:24:21,770 --> 00:24:23,130
Thanks, sweetie.

540
00:24:24,650 --> 00:24:25,850
Sweetie?

541
00:24:26,250 --> 00:24:28,270
You two are really going out?

542
00:24:28,270 --> 00:24:29,490
Of course.

543
00:24:30,430 --> 00:24:31,450
Wow.

544
00:24:35,650 --> 00:24:36,350
Ugh, enough.

545
00:24:43,050 --> 00:24:44,450
What's going on here?

546
00:24:44,550 --> 00:24:46,030
Dad, what are you doing here?

547
00:24:46,030 --> 00:24:46,890
What about the door?

548
00:24:47,750 --> 00:24:50,150
Ozzak forgot his keys again.

549
00:24:51,350 --> 00:24:52,650
Lexa isn't here by any chance, is he?

550
00:24:52,820 --> 00:24:53,440
Why?

551
00:24:54,550 --> 00:24:55,650
Because I know everything.

552
00:24:58,250 --> 00:24:59,150
What did I tell you?

553
00:24:59,370 --> 00:24:59,930
Hello.

554
00:25:00,350 --> 00:25:01,350
Who's this?

555
00:25:01,850 --> 00:25:03,830
Well, this is Renata, a classmate.

556
00:25:03,830 --> 00:25:04,390
What's she doing here?

557
00:25:04,750 --> 00:25:06,050
They came to visit me.

558
00:25:06,050 --> 00:25:06,830
With Lexa.

559
00:25:11,060 --> 00:25:12,580
You said you'd be home alone.

560
00:25:12,720 --> 00:25:14,500
And you said you wouldn't be coming back.

561
00:25:14,560 --> 00:25:16,760
How can I not come back when I know what I know?

562
00:25:17,260 --> 00:25:18,220
What's going on with you and Lexa?

563
00:25:19,240 --> 00:25:20,840
Dad, you've completely lost it.

564
00:25:21,750 --> 00:25:23,150
There's nothing between me and Lexa.

565
00:25:23,860 --> 00:25:24,300
What?

566
00:25:25,850 --> 00:25:27,550
You think I'm blind?

567
00:25:27,650 --> 00:25:30,410
That I don't see how he's always here, bringing you oranges.

568
00:25:30,490 --> 00:25:32,870
And don't think I don't know about those poems.

569
00:25:33,250 --> 00:25:34,030
There's this.

570
00:25:34,030 --> 00:25:36,150
Fine, okay, so he tried, yeah.

571
00:25:36,350 --> 00:25:36,950
See?

572
00:25:37,090 --> 00:25:37,970
But that was ages ago.

573
00:25:39,150 --> 00:25:40,250
He's got a girlfriend now.

574
00:25:42,550 --> 00:25:43,250
Lexa?

575
00:25:43,780 --> 00:25:44,160
Yeah.

576
00:25:45,050 --> 00:25:45,770
This is Renata.

577
00:25:46,790 --> 00:25:47,170
What?

578
00:25:47,950 --> 00:25:48,970
Renda, I'm sorry.

579
00:25:48,970 --> 00:25:50,290
I'm sorry, but Dad will understand.

580
00:25:50,830 --> 00:25:53,150
Dad, she has a terrible life.

581
00:25:53,270 --> 00:25:54,810
Her father is a crazy nutcase.

582
00:25:54,890 --> 00:25:58,330
He thinks that if she starts dating a boy, she'll be pregnant within a week.

583
00:25:58,810 --> 00:26:02,770
He goes through her things, makes scenes, to find out if she has a boyfriend.

584
00:26:03,150 --> 00:26:03,930
Right, Renda?

585
00:26:04,150 --> 00:26:04,850
Well, yeah.

586
00:26:06,350 --> 00:26:08,470
And there's nothing sexual between you and Lexa, right?

587
00:26:08,470 --> 00:26:09,810
Absolutely not.

588
00:26:11,350 --> 00:26:13,350
Lexa, would you ever think of that?

589
00:26:13,380 --> 00:26:13,780
No.

590
00:26:13,780 --> 00:26:17,480
And this is exactly what her dad can't understand.

591
00:26:17,750 --> 00:26:19,250
But you'd understand, right?

592
00:26:20,150 --> 00:26:20,650
Well, I do.

593
00:26:23,550 --> 00:26:26,470
Please, just never tell anyone you saw them here together, okay?

594
00:26:27,090 --> 00:26:27,490
Please.

595
00:26:29,250 --> 00:26:31,670
I won't go spreading it around.

596
00:26:31,670 --> 00:26:32,570
Don't worry.

597
00:26:33,550 --> 00:26:35,150
I should get going.

598
00:26:39,850 --> 00:26:43,150
Well, what are you waiting for, sweetie?

599
00:26:44,880 --> 00:26:45,700
Wow.

600
00:26:54,640 --> 00:26:56,440
You don't have it easy either.

601
00:26:56,680 --> 00:26:57,900
Goodbye, Mr. Pacovsky.

602
00:26:58,240 --> 00:26:59,140
Bye, bye, bye.

603
00:27:04,850 --> 00:27:07,150
Listen, what did she mean that you don't have it easy?

604
00:27:08,650 --> 00:27:11,750
You know, how Ozzak keeps breaking down the door and I have to deal with it.

605
00:27:12,350 --> 00:27:13,250
Right.

606
00:27:13,350 --> 00:27:18,050
Well, I'm off, even if I leave right now, I might still make it for the lagers.

607
00:27:34,050 --> 00:27:36,750
Iva, I came to ask who I'm actually going out with.

608
00:27:37,050 --> 00:27:38,050
Because I don't think it's Machova.

609
00:27:41,750 --> 00:27:42,450
That's good.

610
00:27:44,250 --> 00:27:45,950
And with you?

611
00:27:47,050 --> 00:27:51,180
Well, the truth is, today was the first time I was actually glad to see you walk through the door.

612
00:27:51,450 --> 00:27:53,150
But that was an exceptional situation.

613
00:27:54,050 --> 00:27:55,950
And now things will go back to normal.

614
00:27:56,550 --> 00:27:58,150
So just friends again.

615
00:27:58,850 --> 00:27:59,650
Friends.

616
00:28:00,210 --> 00:28:00,610
Sure.

617
00:28:02,750 --> 00:28:04,150
Can we at least play Crazy Eights?

618
00:28:06,280 --> 00:28:06,780
Crazy Eights?

619
00:28:06,900 --> 00:28:07,560
Out.

620
00:28:14,250 --> 00:28:20,150
I'm Emil Hacha, all day I'm scheming what he'll do next.

621
00:28:20,750 --> 00:28:27,850
He's amazed, Benes is amazed, from London I only hear reproaches.

622
00:28:28,650 --> 00:28:37,250
The Munich Agreement, yeah I wave my right hand, I'm Emil Hacha.

623
00:28:38,550 --> 00:28:39,460
Who was that?

624
00:28:39,460 --> 00:28:40,260
Out.
